Chapter 1. Admin Guide

1.1. Overview

   The rust_refer_handler module tracks SIP REFER transactions and
   their associated NOTIFY messages to provide a complete state
   machine for call transfer tracking. The module maintains
   per-worker transfer state keyed by Call-ID.

   This module is useful for monitoring the progress of SIP call
   transfers (blind and attended) and taking action based on
   transfer success or failure.

1.2. How it works

   The module implements a REFER/NOTIFY state machine with four
   states:

     * pending  - REFER received, no NOTIFY yet
     * trying   - NOTIFY with 100 Trying received
     * success  - NOTIFY with 2xx status received
     * failed   - NOTIFY with 3xx-6xx status received

   Terminal states (success, failed) are sticky: once a transfer
   reaches a terminal state, subsequent NOTIFY messages do not
   change the status. The notify_count is still incremented.

   The script is responsible for parsing the Refer-To header and
   sipfrag status codes and passing them as parameters to the
   module functions. This keeps the module simple and testable.

   Stale REFER state is automatically expired after expire_secs.
   When the number of tracked transfers exceeds max_pending, an
   automatic sweep removes expired entries.

1.3. Dependencies

1.3.1. OpenSIPS Modules

   The following modules must be loaded before this module:
     * None.

1.3.2. External Libraries or Applications

   The following libraries or applications must be installed
   before running OpenSIPS with this module loaded:
     * None.

1.4. Exported Parameters

1.4.1. max_pending (integer)

   Maximum number of REFER transactions tracked per worker process.
   When this limit is reached, a sweep is triggered to remove
   expired entries.

   Default value is "1000".

   Example 1.1. Set max_pending parameter
...
modparam("rust_refer_handler", "max_pending", 2000)
...

1.4.2. expire_secs (integer)

   Time in seconds after which a tracked REFER transaction is
   considered stale and eligible for automatic removal.

   Default value is "300" (5 minutes).

   Example 1.2. Set expire_secs parameter
...
modparam("rust_refer_handler", "expire_secs", 600)
...

1.5. Exported Functions

1.5.1. rust_handle_refer(refer_to)

   Record a new REFER transaction. The Call-ID is automatically
   extracted from the SIP message. The transfer state is
   initialized to "pending".

   If a REFER for the same Call-ID already exists, it is
   overwritten with fresh state.

   Parameters:
     * refer_to (string) - The value of the Refer-To header.
       Typically $hdr(Refer-To). This parameter is mandatory.

   Return values:
     * 1 - REFER recorded successfully
     * -1 - error (missing parameter, no Call-ID, or uninitialized
       worker)

   This function can be used from REQUEST_ROUTE, FAILURE_ROUTE,
   and ONREPLY_ROUTE.

   Example 1.3. rust_handle_refer usage
...
route {
    if (is_method("REFER")) {
        if (rust_handle_refer("$hdr(Refer-To)")) {
            sl_send_reply(202, "Accepted");
        } else {
            sl_send_reply(500, "Internal Error");
        }
    }
}
...

1.5.2. rust_handle_notify(call_id, status_code)

   Process a NOTIFY message for a tracked REFER transaction.
   Updates the state machine based on the sipfrag status code:

     * 100       -> trying
     * 200-299   -> success (terminal)
     * 300-699   -> failed (terminal)

   Parameters:
     * call_id (string) - The Call-ID of the dialog the NOTIFY
       belongs to. Typically $ci. This parameter is mandatory.
     * status_code (string) - The SIP status code from the
       message/sipfrag body. Parsed as an integer internally.
       This parameter is mandatory.

   Return values:
     * 1 - NOTIFY processed (matching REFER found)
     * -1 - no matching REFER found for this Call-ID, or error

   This function can be used from REQUEST_ROUTE, FAILURE_ROUTE,
   and ONREPLY_ROUTE.

   Example 1.4. rust_handle_notify usage
...
route {
    if (is_method("NOTIFY")) {
        # Parse sipfrag body for status code
        if (rust_handle_notify("$ci", "$var(sipfrag_code)")) {
            sl_send_reply(200, "OK");
        } else {
            sl_send_reply(481, "Subscription does not exist");
        }
    }
}
...

1.5.3. rust_refer_status(call_id)

   Query the current status of a tracked REFER transaction. Sets
   $var(refer_status) to one of: "pending", "trying", "success",
   "failed", or "unknown" (if no matching REFER is found).

   Parameters:
     * call_id (string) - The Call-ID to query. Typically $ci.
       This parameter is mandatory.

   Return values:
     * 1 - status found; $var(refer_status) set to the status
       string
     * -1 - no matching REFER found; $var(refer_status) set to
       "unknown"

   This function can be used from REQUEST_ROUTE, FAILURE_ROUTE,
   and ONREPLY_ROUTE.

   Example 1.5. rust_refer_status usage
...
route[check_transfer] {
    if (rust_refer_status("$ci")) {
        xlog("L_INFO", "transfer $ci status: $var(refer_status)\n");
        if ($var(refer_status) == "success") {
            # Transfer completed successfully
        }
        if ($var(refer_status) == "failed") {
            # Transfer failed — take recovery action
        }
    }
}
...

1.6. Exported Pseudo-Variables

1.6.1. $var(refer_status)

   The current status of a tracked REFER transaction. Set by
   rust_refer_status(). Possible values:

     * "pending"  - REFER received, awaiting NOTIFY
     * "trying"   - 100 Trying received
     * "success"  - 2xx received (transfer succeeded)
     * "failed"   - 3xx-6xx received (transfer failed)
     * "unknown"  - no matching REFER found

1.7. Exported Statistics

1.7.1. active_transfers

   Number of currently tracked REFER transactions (not expired).

1.7.2. completed

   Number of REFER transactions that reached "success" state.

1.7.3. failed

   Number of REFER transactions that reached "failed" state.

1.7.4. expired

   Number of REFER transactions that were swept due to expiry.

1.7.5. unknown_notify

   Number of NOTIFY messages received with no matching REFER.

   Example 1.6. Complete opensips.cfg example
...
loadmodule "rust_refer_handler.so"

modparam("rust_refer_handler", "max_pending", 1000)
modparam("rust_refer_handler", "expire_secs", 300)

route {
    if (is_method("REFER")) {
        if (rust_handle_refer("$hdr(Refer-To)")) {
            xlog("L_INFO", "REFER tracked: $ci -> $hdr(Refer-To)\n");
            sl_send_reply(202, "Accepted");
        } else {
            sl_send_reply(500, "Internal Error");
        }
        exit;
    }

    if (is_method("NOTIFY")) {
        # Extract sipfrag status from body (example assumes $rb parsing)
        rust_handle_notify("$ci", "$var(sipfrag_code)");
        sl_send_reply(200, "OK");
        exit;
    }
}

route[check_transfer] {
    rust_refer_status("$ci");
    xlog("L_INFO", "Transfer $ci: $var(refer_status)\n");

    switch ($var(refer_status)) {
        case "success":
            xlog("L_INFO", "Transfer completed successfully\n");
            break;
        case "failed":
            xlog("L_WARN", "Transfer failed\n");
            break;
        case "trying":
            xlog("L_DBG", "Transfer in progress\n");
            break;
    }
}
...
